To display the hierarchical relationships of a selected concept in React, you can build a component using Ant Design or simple HTML elements to represent the structure. Let's create a component that shows the selected concept in the center with its parent and child concepts around it. We'll use `List` from Ant Design to display the parent and child groups.

First, ensure you have Ant Design installed and imported in your project:

```bash
npm install antd
```

```jsx
import { List, Typography } from 'antd';

const { Title, Text } = Typography;
```

Now, let's design the hierarchy display:

```jsx
// This component will render the concept hierarchy
const ConceptHierarchy = ({ concept, groupsIn, groupedUnder }) => {
  return (
    <div style={{ textAlign: 'center' }}>
      {/* List of groups the concept belongs to (parents) */}
      {groupsIn && groupsIn.length > 0 && (
        <>
          <Text type="secondary">Belongs to:</Text>
          <List
            size="small"
            bordered
            dataSource={groupsIn}
            renderItem={(group) => <List.Item>{group.name}</List.Item>}
          />
        </>
      )}

      {/* Selected concept - displayed prominently */}
      <Title level={3}>{concept.name}</Title>

      {/* List of groups under the concept (children) */}
      {groupedUnder && groupedUnder.length > 0 && (
        <>
          <Text type="secondary">Groups:</Text>
          <List
            size="small"
            bordered
            dataSource={groupedUnder}
            renderItem={(group) => <List.Item>{group.name}</List.Item>}
          />
        </>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};

// ... inside your main component's return statement
{selectedConcept && (
  <ConceptHierarchy
    concept={selectedConcept.concept}
    groupsIn={selectedConcept.groups_in}
    groupedUnder={selectedConcept.grouped_under}
  />
)}
```

Explanation:

- We create a new `ConceptHierarchy` component that takes the `concept`, `groupsIn`, and `groupedUnder` as props.
- We use Ant Design's `List` to display the parent concepts ("Belongs to") and child concepts ("Groups") if they exist. These lists are only displayed if there are related concepts to show.
- For the selected concept, we use an Ant Design `Title` to make it stand out as the central concept.

In this layout, the selected concept appears larger and centered, with the parent and children concepts displayed in lists above and below. You can further style these elements to fit your application's design.

Remember to handle the case where a concept might be both a parent and a child in different relationships, and adjust your UI as needed to represent this.

For more sophisticated layouts, consider creating a custom component that visually represents the hierarchy as a tree or graph. However, for a simple hierarchical display, the approach outlined above should be functional and easy to implement with Ant Design components.
